🧵 Cooperative Scheduling and osYield()
Overview

In this system, scheduling follows a cooperative model, where each thread runs until it explicitly yields control of the CPU. The scheduler does not preempt tasks automatically.

A running thread must call:

osYield();

to voluntarily request a context switch.

Design Idea

Instead of performing a direct context switch inside osYield(), the system leverages the SysTick exception mechanism to reuse the existing interrupt-based scheduling flow.

This ensures:

consistent context switch handling inside ISR context
reuse of SysTick handler logic
minimal duplication of scheduler code
Implementation of osYield()

The function forces a context switch by triggering the SysTick exception in software.

Step 1: Reset SysTick current value
SysTick->VAL = 0;

This clears the current counter value, ensuring the SysTick timer logic does not delay the interrupt.

Step 2: Pend SysTick exception
SCB->ICSR |= (1 << 26);  // PENDSTSET

This sets the SysTick pending bit, requesting the SysTick interrupt to be serviced as soon as possible.

Step 3: SysTick interrupt execution

Once the interrupt is taken, the CPU enters:

SysTick_Handler()

Inside this handler, the scheduler performs:

saving the current thread context
selecting the next ready thread
restoring the next thread context
Execution Flow
Thread calls osYield()
        ↓
SysTick set to pending (ICSR.PENDSTSET)
        ↓
CPU enters SysTick_Handler()
        ↓
Scheduler runs
        ↓
Context switch occurs
Key Point

osYield() does not perform a context switch directly.
It requests a context switch by triggering the SysTick exception, and the actual scheduling happens inside the SysTick ISR.
